Class InvalidCapacityException

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable
    public class InvalidCapacityException
extends java.lang.Exception

    InvalidCapacityException is an Exception that is used by non-default constructors of containers that receive a desired starting capacity in our code base. For reasons of efficiency, it is often important that the container is internally pre-allocated to a desired capacity so that the getFirst few insertions are performed quite fast. For example, ArrayList() (the ArrayList's default constructor}) initializes the ArrayList with a default capacity of 10 (ten) to avoid paying for the resizing of the container for the getFirst 10 insertions of elements.

    In many object-oriented programming languages such as Java, there is no way to notify the caller of a constructor of an underlying error in the constructor body other than throwing some kind of Throwable. For example, the Java runtime would throw an OutOfMemoryError if the heap runs out of memory during object creation.
